    Visualising Gun Crime with Folium

    Theo Alli

    2018-05-31 21:09

    Visualising 2017 Gun Violence in America With Folium¶

    In this piece i'll be using the Folium package in python to visualise gun violence in the United States in 2017. The folium package allows you to visualise your data in python using the leaflet.js library. The end result is great looking maps that can be displayed in a web browser, which only require a few lines of code.

    In [41]:
    import pandas as pd
import folium

    To begin, let's load the data. I've preprocessed the original kaggle dataset so it only contains data from 2017. I'll be also using population data from the U.S. Census Beaureau to calculate incident rates.

    In [42]:
    df = pd.read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/t-alli/gun-violence-plots/master/2017_gun_data.csv')
population = pd.read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/t-alli/gun-violence-plots/master/2017%20population%20data.csv')
df.head()

    To visualise the choropleth, We'll need to merge the population data and the gun violence data so that we can calculate the number of incidents per 100,000 people:

    In [44]:
    grouped = df.groupby(['state'])[['n_killed', 'n_injured']].sum()
choro_df= pd.merge(population, grouped, right_index=True, left_on='state')
choro_df.head()
    Out[44]:
    state 2017 Population n_killed n_injured
    0 Alabama 4874747 543 856
    1 Alaska 739795 68 66
    2 Arizona 7016270 280 294
    3 Arkansas 3004279 214 430
    4 California 39536653 1383 1911

    Let's now create new columns containing the incident rates:

    In [45]:
    choro_df['killed per 100000'] = (choro_df['n_killed'] / choro_df['2017 Population']) * 100000
choro_df['incidents per 100000'] = (choro_df['n_killed'] + choro_df['n_injured'])/ choro_df['2017 Population'] * 100000
choro_df.head()

    Now it's time to visualise the choropleths. To do so, we first create a map object in folium:

    In [46]:
    n_killed_map = folium.Map(location=[38.0215482, -95.471191], tiles='OpenStreetMap', zoom_start=4.3)

    Then we need to add the choropleth to the map. To do that we'll need to pass a geojson file to the choropleth function, which contains the co-ordinates for the state boundaries. We'll also need to pass the gun violence data to the function as a dataframe, specifying the index and the values we want to represent on the choropleth.

    We then link our dataframe with the state co-ordinates in the geojson file, producing a visual representation of 2017 gun violence deaths per 100,000 people by state:

    In [47]:
    n_killed_map.choropleth(geo_data='https://raw.githubusercontent.com/t-alli/gun-violence-plots/master/us-states_processed.json', 
                        data=choro_df, 
                        columns =['state', 'killed per 100000'], 
                        key_on='feature.id', fill_color='YlOrRd', 
                        legend_name='No. killed per 100,000 in 2017')
n_killed_map
    Out[47]:

    The 2nd choropleth shows the number of gun violence incidents (deaths or injuries) per 100,000 people:

    In [48]:
    n_incidents_map = folium.Map(location=[38.0215482, -95.471191], tiles='OpenStreetMap', zoom_start=4.3)

n_incidents_map.choropleth(geo_data='https://raw.githubusercontent.com/t-alli/gun-violence-plots/master/us-states_processed.json', 
                  data=choro_df, 
                  columns =['state', 'incidents per 100000'], 
                  key_on='feature.id', fill_color='PuRd', 
                  legend_name='No. incidents per 100,000 in 2017')

n_incidents_map
    Out[48]:

    We can also use folium to generate a heatmap of deaths as a result of gun violence. To do that we simply create another map object, generate the heatmap, then overlay the heatmap on our map of the United States. Note that we're using the 'n_killed' variable as the heatmap weight, hence the 'hotter' regions show areas where gun fatality numbers are high (not accounting for population size).

    In [49]:
    from folium.plugins import HeatMap, FastMarkerCluster

#Create new map object
hm_map = folium.Map(location=[38.0215482, -95.471191], tiles='OpenStreetMap', zoom_start=4.3)

#Prepare our data so we can pass it to the HeatMap function
hm_data = df[['latitude', 'longitude', 'n_killed']].as_matrix().tolist()

#Generate heatmap, and overlay our new map object with the heatmap
HeatMap(hm_data).add_to(hm_map)

#Display the heatmap
hm_map
    Out[49]:

    Finally, we can visualise where any injury or death occured using the FastMarkerCluster function. This function clusters incidents that resulted in deaths deaths by area. To explore the functionality of the FastMarkerCluster, try clicking on one of the clusters.

    In [50]:
    m_cluster = folium.Map(location=[38.0215482, -95.471191], tiles='OpenStreetMap', zoom_start=4.3)
m_cluster.add_child(FastMarkerCluster(df[df['n_killed'] > 0][['latitude', 'longitude']].as_matrix().tolist()))
